default2.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere is no shortage of food in the UK today but there are people who are unable to eat a good diet as they are unable to afford it or access it. Producing more food at the expense of our environments health and 
defaultpotentially public health, is not a solution to this problem. The Marmot review
default into social-related health inequalities in England, ‘Fair Society, Healthy Lives’, sets out a framework for action to ensure social justice, health and sustainability are at t
defaulthe heart of all policies. Recommendations include promoting sustainable local communities, access to good quality green space and sustainable food production.
default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment 
defaultstatistics show that the UK is over 60% self-sufficient in food (or over 70% if you consider only the foods that can actually be grown here). By comparison, we were less than 50% self sufficient for much of the 1930s, 40s, and 50s. So although 
defaultthe UK is
default mo
defaultre self reliant than 
defaultit was 
defaultwe are still part of the global market and as such will be subject to the fluctuations which exist. 
defaultThe UK can play a role in helping to reduce 
defaultthe impact of these fluctuations 
defaultby developing a more sustainable 
defaultand resilient 
defaultappr
defaultoach to 
defaultour domestic agricultural system and so reducing our reliance on imported 
defaultfeedstocks
default and the exposure of our food and farming systems to ext
defaulternal shocks, be they economic, physical or 
defaultenvironmental
default. 
