default7.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIncreasing agricultural specialisation, driven by a narrow focus on efficiency
default,
default has resulted in polarisation 
defaultof production and the loss of mixed, rotational farming that has underpinned good soil, crop and animal husbandry for centuries. Historically farms 
defaultutilised
default rotations which build soil and circulate nutrients. 
defaultMixed farms
default now find it difficult to compete wi
defaultth the extremely specialised arable and livestock systems as the benefits of mixed systems and the externalities (soil degradation, feed and nutrient imports) of intensive systems
default,
default are not reflected in our current economic model
default. This specialisation, conc
defaultentration on just a few major commodity crops and reliance on imported protein (the EU is already reliant on importing three-quarters of protein-rich feed) has left limited diversity, which combined with increasingly unpredictable extremes of weather, leav
defaultes food production vulnerable and lacking resilience.
